## The smell test

Before publishing anything, read it out loud.

If a sentence makes you cringe when you speak it, rewrite it.

If a paragraph feels like it could have been written by anyone
selling anything, rewrite it.

If the whole piece feels like it doesn't sound like you, start
over.

---

## The Kendra test

When writing for THWB or Trellis, ask: "Would Kendra say this?"

If the answer is no, rewrite. Her ear is one of our best quality
controls.

---

## Examples of the voice working

### Good THWB opening (from an essay)

> We tried everything. Notion dashboards. Google Calendar colors.
> A shared grocery list that someone always forgot to check. A
> family meeting that lasted 90 minutes and ended in nobody
> wanting to do another one.
>
> Then one Sunday, we tried something embarrassingly simple. We
> set a 30-minute timer. We opened one document. We answered
> three questions.
>
> It's been two years. We haven't missed a Sunday since.

Why it works: Specific (not "we tried many tools" — we named
them). Honest (admits the 90-minute failure). Concrete (the
30-minute timer, the three questions). Earns the reader's
attention by being truthful.

### Good Trellis section

> The Family Meeting takes 30 minutes. Cy pulls both calendars.
> Walks you through the week day by day. Asks 2-4 questions per
> day. You commit to five decisions. You capture the plan. You
> close with one sentence or one prayer.
>
> You walk into Monday clear.

Why it works: Short sentences. Specific numbers. Product
mechanics are visible. The emotional payoff is the last line,
earned by the mechanics above it.

### Good Cy message

> CY · MORNING, TUESDAY
>
> Jaiye has practice three nights this week. Is there a version
> of the week where he gets two?

Why it works: One observation. One question. Enough specificity
that the parent recognizes their own life. No advice. No judgment.

